5:
W-wait... How could this be? They've
shut down?
8: Do you know this umbrella store?
12:
Yes. The one I bought to go with this
outfit came from here! They were
open just a while ago... I wonder
what happened?
16:
Um, excuse me... Could I talk to you
for a second?
19:
Oh, hello there. You're the lass who
bought from us the other day, aren't
you?
21:
Yes, that's right.
I, uh... would like to know why you've
closed up shop...
23:
Because sales have been quite poor
lately. Plus, I'm not getting any
younger—I figured it was just the
right time to do so.
27:
I can't believe it... What a
shame—your umbrellas were some
of the best I've ever seen!
29:
Are you really going to stop making
them altogether?
31:
That's right. Yes, I took great pains to
make them, but it seems that wasn't
enough.
38:
...No, I understand. Just making a
good product alone does not
guarantee success.
42:
Perhaps you need to rethink your
distribution, or your marketing! If we
can just get your product out to
more people, I'm sure they'll love it!
49:
Ma'am... Would you be willing to wait
a while before closing down the
shop?
52:
I think I can find a way to help you
sell your umbrellas! Please, just let
me help you!
59:
Wh-whoa... This is a LOT of books,
Trista. Are you sure you're not
overdoing it here?
63:
Oh, hi Alk! Perfect timing—I'd like to
get your opinion on something.
66:
I think we can use this, what do you
think?
73:
It's a tradition from Yamato.
Apparently, if you eat fish on that
one particular day, you'll have good
health.
76:
Huh, I didn't know that. I guess I'll
make sure to cook fish on that day
too, just in case it's true!
79:
Yeah, about that... It turns out that
day was entirely made-up!
82: Huh? The whole tradition is a lie?
86:
I mean, not technically a lie, no. It's
more like... a publicity stunt gone
right.
90:
Apparently, a fishmonger tried to
boost sales to his shop by putting
up a poster with a catchy slogan
about how today was THE day to eat
fish.
92:
Anyway, it worked! So much so that
other stores nearby copied him, and
the whole thing became a cultural
phenomenon!
95:
Seriously? Just like that? One poster
led to a whole holiday being created?
99:
Yes. It seems similar marketing
methodologies have been used in
Palpebra as well—to great effect. If
only we could do the same for
umbrellas...
102:
It's almost scary how smart you are,
Trista.
106: R-really? Is that bad? Should I stop?
110:
Ah, no! I didn't mean it that way. I
just meant... you might be on to
something! I think we could really
boost sales with those tactics.
113:
Honestly, you've even piqued my
interest! Is there anything I can help
with?
117:
Yes there is! You see, there's a
legend in Yamato about something
called the Rains of Misfortune...
122:
The Rains of Misfortune? Huh, I've
never heard of that!
124:
Just think about it! The kami cleanse
the world of misfortune at the end of
the year, right? The part they didn't
get around to cleansing ends up
falling from the sky!
126:
...Maybe I should buy an umbrella,
just to be safe.
128:
That might be a good idea! See, that
girl over there is using one! It
matches her kimono perfectly, too.
131:
Looks like you've become the poster
girl for this advertising campaign,
Trista.
136:
D-don't tease me, Alk! This is so
embarrassing...
139:
I was unsure about this whole
scheme at first, but it appears to be
working!
143:
Yep. Have you thought about a
career change? Forget adventuring,
you could be a Guild merchant!
147:
I'm not sure you understand what
that entails. Those merchants are
terrifying, Alk—especially the ones in
the upper echelon of the Guild...
154:
I've learned a lot from this
experience. And, more importantly...
161:
Haha! You should just continue
being an adventurer and do this
sort of thing on the side! Like that
one writer you look up to.
166:
N-no way... I could never compare
myself to Lady Levy.
178:
Absolutely not! It would be
disrespectful to even suggest that!
